        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:52:"CPD Superintendent Garry McCarthy Hates Black People";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:106:"http://www.chicagonow.com/red-cup-adventures/2015/11/cpd-superintendent-garry-mccarthy-hates-black-people/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:115:"http://www.chicagonow.com/red-cup-adventures/2015/11/cpd-superintendent-garry-mccarthy-hates-black-people/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Sat, 28 Nov 2015 13:35:06 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:52:"http://www.chicagonow.com/red-cup-adventures/?p=1045";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9483:"Hate is a strong word…the strongest…which is why I don’t use it capriciously or even in jest. I’ve never heard <strong>Garry McCarthy</strong> state that he hates Black people, but since actions speak louder than words, I have come to this conclusion. I’ve observed Garry McCarthy’s leadership since his appointment in 2011. Though I didn't always agree with his methods, in the beginning I thought he was a good man working for all of the people. But in this last year, he has shown his heart and on the morning of July 8<sup>th</sup>, 2015, I saw him up close and personal and then I knew this truth that Chicago Police Department Superintendent Garry McCarthy hates Black people. But before I tell you what happened on that day, I need to tell you the background story of former Chicago Police Department officer Howard Morgan.

In 2005, Howard Morgan was an African-American, 53-year old husband, father, and grandfather living in the North Lawndale neighborhood. He was a retired Chicago Police Department officer and he was working as a detective assigned to the Burlington Northern Santa Fe railroad. He had no criminal history and was a respected community and church leader. On February 21, 2005 around 1245am, he was driving home from work and was pulled over by two white police officers <b>John Wrigley</b> and <b>Timothy Finley</b>. These two white officers were soon joined by two additional white officers <b>Nicolas Olsen</b> and <b>Eric White</b>. Mr. Morgan said he identified himself as a police officer and that he was carrying a gun. A witness said she saw the officers snatch Mr. Morgan from his van and force him onto one knee. She heard an officer say "Oh shit, he has a gun” and then the four officers opened fire on Mr. Morgan while he lay on the ground. Does that description of the police shooting sound familiar?

The four white officers shot Howard Morgan 28 times…22 of those bullets were fired into Mr. Morgan’s back. None of the four white police officers were seriously injured and none of them spent a night in the hospital. Miraculously, Howard Morgan lived. He was in the hospital for seven months. He was also arrested and charged with four counts of attempted murder. In his first trial, Howard Morgan was found not guilty of firing his weapon, but the jury was hung on the murder convictions. In his second trial (which should have never happened in light of the double jeopardy law), Howard Morgan was wrongly convicted and given 40 years in prison even though he never fired his weapon and was shot 28 times.

In October 2014, I learned of Mr. Morgan’s plight and began helping the family petition Governor Pat Quinn to pardon Howard Morgan. On his last day in office in January 2015, Pat Quinn commuted Howard Morgan’s sentence freeing him from prison. Quinn did not pardon him, which would have erased Mr. Morgan’s guilty conviction. Cook County State’s Attorney Anita Alvarez and the Fraternal Order of Police were extremely vocal in their outrage at Howard Morgan’s release. But I noted that neither Superintendent McCarthy nor Mayor Emanuel weighed in on the issue and I was okay with that. On one side you have one Black police officer’s word against four white police officers' words. So I was okay with the superintendent of CPD staying neutral on a shooting that happened in 2005 which was 6 years before McCarthy came to Chicago. But the morning of July 8<sup>th</sup> that all changed.

On July 8<sup>th</sup>, 2015, Howard Morgan had a hearing with the Illinois Prison Review Board to petition for a full pardon to clear the guilty verdict from his record. With a full pardon, Mr. Morgan would be able to receive his two police pensions (he was a Chicago Police Officer for 8.5 years with 13 CPD commendations and a Burlington Northern Officer for 13 years) and have the option to sue the city for wrongful conviction. Since <strong>Jon Burge</strong> is receiving a CPD pension after torturing confessions from more than 200 Black men, then certainty Mr. Morgan who was shot 28 times…22 times in the back…should be receiving his police pensions. I knew that the Fraternal Order of Police and the State’s Attorney’s Office would be there in full force with guns blazing, but what I didn’t expect was Superintendent Garry McCarthy. When I saw him shaking the hands of the four white officers who tried to assassinate a fellow Black police officer my heart stopped, time stood still, and I knew. Not only did Garry McCarthy attend, he testified in support of the four white officers. He testified that he approves of white officers shooting a Black man 28 times…22 of those bullets in Howard Morgan’s back. I knew then that Garry McCarthy supports shooting Black people because he must hate us and as a Black person I would never feel safe in my city as long as racist Superintendent Garry McCarthy is the leader of the CPD.

I didn’t know on that day that Superintendent Garry McCarthy was actively suppressing a videotape of one of his officers shooting 17-year old Laquan McDonald 16 times…4 times in the back. So in hindsight, Garry McCarthy knew he had a white police officer under his watch who hatefully murdered a young Black boy. Racism, excessive force, and unlawful executions are not new tactics in the Chicago Police Department. Garry McCarthy had seen Officer<strong> Jason Van Dyke</strong> execute Laquan McDonald, but he chose to break his silence to take the stand at Howard Morgan’s hearing and pledge his unwavering support for Officers <strong>John Wrigley, Eric White, Timothy Finley</strong>, and <strong>Nicolas Olsen</strong>. And I’m sure he had Mayor Emanuel's permission to do so.

On November 10, 2015, <a href="http://invisible.institute/news/" target="_blank">the Invisible Institute</a> launched an online database of 56,000 allegations of misconduct complaint records for more than 8,500 Chicago Police officers. Though the Citizen's Police Data Project only covers allegations from March 2011 to September 2015, it is still the most expansive public dataset of its kind. The database finally launched after a decade of ligation waged by the City of Chicago, Chicago Police Department and the Fraternal Order of Police. <a href="http://cpdb.co/data/LdEGgb/citizens-police-data-project" target="_blank">You can click here to go to the CPDP website</a>, type in a CPD officer’s name, and see how many complaints have been filed against that officer in the past four years. Repeat officers, those with 10 or more complaints, make up about 10% of the force but receive 30% of all complaints. These repeat officers average 3.7x as many complaints per officer as the rest of the force. Here’s what I found on the six officers I’ve mention in this article:

<a href="http://cpdb.co/officer/jason-van-dyke/7655" target="_blank">Officer Jason Van Dyke</a> - 20 complaints including conduct unbecoming while off duty

<a href="http://cpdb.co/officer/john-wrigley/8221" target="_blank">Officer John Wrigley</a> - 15 complaints including conduct unbecoming while off duty

<a href="http://cpdb.co/officer/eric-white/8009" target="_blank">Officer Eric White</a> - 4 complaints

<a href="http://cpdb.co/officer/timothy-finley/2232" target="_blank">Officer Timothy Finley</a> - 1 complaint

Officer Nicolas Olsen - 0 complaints

<a href="http://cpdb.co/officer/garry-mc-carthy/4665" target="_blank">Officer Garry Mc Carthy</a> - 2 complaints including bribery / official corruption

Garry McCarthy is the highest paid city employee with an annual salary of $260,004. That’s a lot of money. That’s over a quarter million dollars and I bet he’ll get a pension, just like Jon Burge. How long will the city of Chicago keep paying salaries and pensions to racist cops, torturers and murders? How many million dollar settlements will Mayor Emanuel offer to victims before we say enough? 32% of Chicago’s population are Black and another 28% are Brown. If you are a racist, then you should not be allowed to hold a position of leadership. Garry McCarthy's latest sound bite is that Mayor Emanuel has assured him that he has his back. Garry McCarthy hates Black people and birds of feather, flock together.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Deanna Burrell is still working with Howard Morgan and his family to secure a full pardon. Mr. Morgan was shot 28 times in 2005 which caused irreparable damage to his body. He needs the assistance of a cane to walk and has been denied his police pensions and medical insurance. He and his family have suffered tremendous physical, emotional, and financial stress, but they remain prayerful. In light of the terrible atrocities that the Morgans has endured, please make a donation to the Howard Morgan fund this holiday season. <a href="http://www.freehowardmorgan.com/help-the-campaign.html" target="_blank">Click here to donate.</a>

